[4] UK (Northern Ireland)
Date: Tue 25 Jun 2019
Source: Belfast Telegraph [edited]
https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/annual-cases-of-whooping-cough-almost-trebles-in-northern-ireland-38249413.html


Northern Ireland has seen a significant increase this year in cases of whooping cough. The Public Health Agency (PHA) recorded 44 cases to [19 Jun 2019], compared to 16 reported during the same period last year [2018].

Just over 1/5 were in infants under 6 months of age and so too young to be protected by their routine childhood immunisations. The PHA urged pregnant women here to receive the vaccine between 16 and 32 weeks of their pregnancy.

A spokesman said: "Whooping cough continues to circulate in Northern Ireland and every 3 to four 4 it is normal to see increased activity, which is what we are experiencing this year [2019]. It is therefore really important that women receive the pertussis vaccine during every pregnancy so that their baby is protected against whooping cough in their 1st months of life."

[Byline: Christopher Leebody]

